Column Comment.0: STORE ID: Unique identifier for the data store location.
Column Comment.1: STRUCTURE OBSERVATION NUMBER: Unique identifier for this observation of adata storage structure.
Column Comment.2: ACTIVE INDICATOR: A Y or N flag indicating whether this row of data is currentlyeither active/valid (Y) or inactive/invalid (N).
Column Comment.3: DIMENSION HEIGHT: the height of the data store, important for determining whatsize objects can fit into the space.
Column Comment.6: DIMENSION LENGTH: the length of the data store, important for determining whatsize objects can fit into the space.
Column Comment.9: DIMENSION WEIGHT: the weight capacity of the data store, important fordetermining what size objects can fit into the space.
Column Comment.12: DIMENSION WIDTH: the width of the data store, important for determining what sizeobjects can fit into the space.
Column Comment.15: EFFECTIVE DATE: date on which the data in this row came into effect.
Column Comment.16: EXPIRY DATE: Date on which the data in this row of data was no longer in effect.
Column Comment.17: LOWER CONTAINED STORAGE ID: Useful only in cases where store IDs areassigned in sequence. Can be used to indicate for an upper level in the hierarchy,what the store ID is for the range of subordinate store IDs that have thisconfiguration. For example, in a Bay, Store IDs 1000 - 5000 may have the describedconfiguration.
Column Comment.18: ROW_MANAGEMENT_GUID: This value may be used to provide a global uniqueidentifier for this row of data. Use of this column is not mandatory, but if used,optional PPDM NOT NULL and UNIQUE INDEX constraints provided in the datamodel DDL shouldbe created.
Column Comment.19: REMARK: Narrative remarks about this row of data.
Column Comment.20: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.21: TOTAL CAPACITY: the total number of data store units in this one that have thedescribed configuration.
Column Comment.22: UPPER CONTAINED STORAGE ID: Useful only in cases where store IDs areassigned in sequence. Can be used to indicate for an upper level in the hierarchy,what the store ID is for the range of subordinate store IDs that have thisconfiguration. For example, in a Bay, Store IDs 1000 - 5000 may have the describedconfiguration.
Column Comment.23: USED CAPACITY: the total number of data store units within this one with thedescribed configuration that are currently occupied or unavailable for use.
Column Comment.24: USED CAPACITY DATE: the date when the used capacity was last calculated ormeasured.
Column Comment.25: ROW CHANGED BY: Application login id of the user who last changed the row.
Column Comment.26: ROW CHANGED DATE: System date of the last time the row was changed.
Column Comment.27: ROW CREATED BY: System user who created this row of data.
Column Comment.28: ROW CREATED DATE: Date that the row was created on.
Column Comment.29: ROW_EFFECTIVE_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of datais effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row of data wasmade available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.30: ROW_EXPIRY_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of data isno longer effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row ofdata was no longer available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.31: PPDM ROW QUALITY: A set of values indicating the quality of data in this row,usually with reference to the method or procedures used to load the data, althoughother types of quality reference are permitted.
